<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-415-746  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 415 746.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  June 1989 v62 n6 p65(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A case for programmable controllers in process control. (includesrelated article on the gold refining process)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musterer, Roy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Advances in programmable logic controller (PLC) design andcapabilities have made it a viable alternative to distributedprocess control systems (DCSs) for many process controloperations, often with superior price-performance.andP;  The selectionof a particular technology is frequently a function of designphilosophy, as the similarities between the two are greater thantheir differences.andP;  Advantages of PLCs in process control includegreater flexibility for customizing, maintainability byelectricians rather than requiring programmers and engineers,superior connectivity, superior ruggedness and reliability withoutthe need for air-conditioned containments, improved real-timeperformance at lower cost, and a growing list of proven processsoftware tools and interfaces.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Programmable ControllersDistributed SystemsPerformance ImprovementProcess ControlComparison.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   Integration of small PLCs on peer-to-peer link to a host PLC.andO;(chart)Several ways to configure PLCs for use in a process controlsystem. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>